<br>
1) You are skill capped at (level * 5) in foreign languages.<br>
<br>
2) You can only get one language skill increase per [real] hour, unless you zone.<br>
<br>
3) You can only get skill increases through hearing a language spoken in /group or /say, not /tell, /shout, /guild or /auction.  Also, you must be in the same zone as a person to get a language skill increment from them in groupsay.<br>
<br>
4) You can only get a skill increment from listening to a person speak a language who is equal to, or better than you are at speaking that language (applicable to all servers).<br>
<br>
Basically the only way to get any respectable degree of skill at understanding and speaking other languages is by &quot;power-teaching&quot;.<br>
<br>
There are two methods that work effectively for this.  The best way to teach somebody another language is to get another person who speaks that language well, and get on opposite sides of a zone line (for example, have one you stand at the East Freeport to West Freeport zoneline on the EF side, and you stand on the WF side).  Create a social key that has five lines of /g text.  Switch to the language you want to teach.  Turn on the group chat filter to cut down on spam.  And hammer the hotkey.  When the person you're attempting to teach gets a skill increment, they should zone to receive a lesson from the teacher on the other side.  And so they keep zoning back and forth.  This is a good way to teach multiple people a language at once.  You could do this with only one teacher, but it would require that you zone with them to continue the lesson (inconvenient if you're trying to teach more than one person at a time).<br>
<br>
The other method that works well is &quot;bootstrapping&quot;.  This is what you do when you've got a friend, and you both want to learn the same language, but neither of you have much skill in it.  First one of you needs to get at least a single point of skill in the language, either through a guild trainer, or by learning it from somebody who speaks the language.  Then you set up near a zone line and spam each other with a social key in groupsay.  When you both get skill language increments (nod at each other when you do), then you zone and repeat.  In this way you can go from one of you having only a single point of skill, to both of you having the language mastered in about an hour and a half, if you are fast zoners (and have good intelligence).<br>
<br>
It's best to pick zones which are relatively small and unpopulated.  Lake Rathe/Arena works well, as do the two Felwithe city zones. <p><FONT FACE="Comic Sans MS">--Tukka</FONT><BR>
